fields.information: Estar refers to transient conditions. For example 'Yo estoy feliz', I am happy.  It is also used when describing something in the moment, or describing locations (except when describing events). For example, 'el hombre está en la casa', the man is in the house. Also use estar to describe the taste of food. For example, 'este tapa está deliciosa', this tapa is delicious.

fields.english_translation: The girl is ten years old

fields.information: Alternative is 'Mi nombre is...' Which literally means - My name is...
If you’re ordering things that are far away from the waiter (the menu, the check, a fork, a slice of lemon), use traer. (Also, if you’re asking for things that are close to the waiter, use dar.)

pk: Para mi, un vaso de jugo de naranja

fields.english_translation: For me, a glass of orange juice
fields.information: Ordering for yourself is simple: use 'para mí' and the item you want

pk: Perdona, nos traes la carta, por favor

fields.english_translation: Excuse me, bring us the menu, please

fields.information: If you’re ordering food or drinks, you can use both, poner or traer.

Ser refers to more permanent traits of someone or something. For example, 'ella es alta', she is tall. Therefore ser is used for occupations, relationships ('eres mi hermano', you are my brother) and  possessions ('es mi libro', it's my book).
If you’re ordering food or drinks, you can use both, poner or traer.

pk: Y a mí me pones un cortado

fields.english_translation: And (to me) put me an espresso

fields.information: Literally translates to - What do you call yourself?

fields.english_translation: How many brothers do you have?
Can you put me a coca-cola?

pk: ¿Me traes un vaso de agua, cuando puedas?

fields.english_translation: Bring me a glass of water, whenever you can?
fields.information: “I”-focused requests sound weird in Spanish (eg: ¿podría tener…? - can I have?). Instead, focus on what we want the other person to do (¿me traes…? - bring me?; ¿me puedes traer…? - can you bring me?).
